##NEW ADVANCES IN VACCINE DESIGN! The super-clean structure of the novel coronavirus s protein has been mapped successfully, but a practical vaccine will take more time

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yesterday, Science published a new paper on the new coronavirus by Jason McLellan's team at the University of Texas at Austin. The team used freeze electron microscopy to disentangle the superclean structure of the novel coronavirus s protein. The work is important for developing vaccines and antiviral drug.

"When we learned it was a coronavirus, we felt we had to act immediately, " McLellan said, "because we may have been one of the first to acquire the structure of the coronavirus, we know exactly which mutations to make, because we have shown that these mutations work for other coronaviruses as well. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | near-atomic resolution structure of a novel coronavirus s protein trimer of 3.5 angstroms (Source: paper)

The affinity of the novel coronavirus receptor was much higher than that of SARS

Because the new coronavirus and SARS virus belong to the same coronavirus, and have some similarities, the comparison of the two viruses has been one of the focuses of scientists.

Since the outbreak of SARS, much research has been done on the molecular biology of coronavirus and its invasion mechanism.

The last third of the coronavirus genome mainly encodes structural proteins, including spike, s, e, M and N proteins. Among them, s protein mainly through the host cell receptor binding mediates the virus invasion, and determines the virus tissue or host tropism.

Therefore, the study of s protein is the most important to explain the process of virus invasion, the prevention and control of virus and the development of antiviral drug. Previous research by Shi Zhengli's team at the COVID-19 has shown that the key to infecting human cells is the binding of the s protein to ACE2.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | structural comparison between the s protein of 2019-nCoV and the s protein of SARS-CoV (Source: paper)

Mclellan's team analyzed the s protein using freeze electron microscopy and the s protein's affinity for ACE2 using the Surface plasmon resonance technique. The human ACE2 protein was found to be 10 to 20 times more likely to bind to the COVID-19 s protein than to the SARS virus s protein.

From the point of view of infectivity, the new coronavirus was obviously higher than SARS virus. Data released by the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention in the past few days showed that the number of new crown disease Basic reproduction number (R0, the average number of people infected by an infected person with another person) was 3.77, higher than that of SARS (0.85-3) .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. | comparison of the affinities of s protein with ACE2 of neocoronavirus (top) and SARS virus (bottom)(Source: paper)

The study confirms that the new coronavirus is more likely to enter human cells, but the paper says further research is needed to test this possibility.

In an interview with the media, some experts said that the infectivity of the virus is not only related to the difficulty of getting into cells, but also related to the immunity of the body, the speed of replication of the virus in cells and other factors. Therefore, receptor affinity is 10 times higher than SARS, does not mean that the infectivity is 10 times higher than SARS.

Next step: using protein molecules as "probes"

S Protein is a key component of new coronavirus infection and a key target for the development of new coronavirus vaccine and antibody inhibitors.

Previously, without knowing the structure of the s protein of the new coronavirus, the development of new coronaviruses was mostly based on the predicted structure, or the protein structure of the SARS virus, which is similar to the new coronavirus.

Knowing the structure of the new cap allows for more precise follow-up. The structure they got, the researchers believe, represents only the extracellular portion of the s protein, but is sufficient to trigger an immune response in the body and could therefore be used in vaccine development.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | NEOCORONAVIRUS (NIAID-RML)

The University of Wisconsin System has been at the forefront of protein engineering to fight disease. Understanding the 3D structure of proteins, the institute could create "locks" and "keys" that fit those proteins, either to promote or discourage molecular interactions.

The agency had been trying to find a way to block the new coronavirus. They are developing "Flu Glue" to protect against the Flu virus, which binds better to the proteins on the virus's coat. The new protein structure helps them create similar microproteins.

In addition, mRNA-1273, a candidate vaccine for MSB, clover biology and Moderna, also encodes the s protein.

Mclellan's team had done a lot of work on coronaviruses, including the SARS and Mers viruses, and had a lot of experience. But the team believes the key to this success lies in the latest technology from Cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) .

Next, they plan to use the protein molecules to attack the new coronavirus in another way: Using the molecules as "probes" to isolate naturally occurring antibodies from patients who have been infected with COVID-19 and have successfully recovered.

In Large enough quantities, these antibodies can help treat viral infections shortly after exposure.

Practical vaccines will take more time

The paper, which was published Feb. 17 on Biorxiv, a preprint platform, was published in Science in less than three days, a process that usually takes several months.

Most of the work of this thesis is completed by Daniel WRAPP and Wang nian-shuang. The team spent 12 days reconstructing the 3D atomic scale map and submitting the manuscript after only two weeks of designing the protein samples from the virus genome.

Although the publication process has been a green light, the development of a vaccine requires some basic processes and time, which is not very short.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
From left to right: Daniel WRAPP, Jason McLellan and mclellanlab.org  

Earlier, Li Lanjuan, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and a member of the National Health Commission's expert panel, said in an interview with CCTV that the new vaccine could be available in as little as three months. The H1N1 vaccine took 87 days from the time it was obtained to the time it was approved. Given current technology and progress, is three months enough time?

Although we now know the structure of the s protein, developing a vaccine still requires many iterations, many steps, to determine the most appropriate point.

"It is very difficult to successfully develop a vaccine to prevent or manage a public health crisis. It usually takes a lot of time and money, " Brad Loncar, an American biotech investor, told the BBC.

After the vaccine samples have been developed, a complex process of R & D, Animal Testing, clinical trials, and approval has to be completed before State Food and Drug Administration can be approved for specific preventive and therapeutic applications. There is also the question of whether mass vaccine production can be completed in the short term.

At present, the number of companies publicly announcing the development of new coronavirus vaccines has reached 19, mainly including recombinant protein vaccines, DNA vaccines and Mrna Vaccines. The recombinant protein vaccine project led by the Chinese Academy of Sciences has entered the animal experimental stage.

Products expected to enter animal trials could enter clinical trials as early as mid-april.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Source: Pharmaporum)

The following is a compilation of some domestic and international developments in the research and development of new Crown Vaccines:

On February 19, Sanofi Pasteur, Sanofi's Global Vaccine Division, announced a partnership with the U.S. Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Agency (Barda) to accelerate the development of a new coronavirus vaccine using a platform of advanced gene recombination technology.

On February 18, Guangdong Adenovirus vector vaccine is expected to start animal experiments before February 28.

On February 15, Zhang Xinmin, director of the China Biotechnology Development Center of the Ministry of Science and Technology, said that some vaccine varieties have already entered the animal testing stage; Guanhao Biology said that the vaccine project is still under development and that it will be at least a year before it is ready for clinical use; Konsino biology is trying to develop a MRNA vaccine.

On Feb. 13, Inovio said it had developed a vaccine against COVID-19 on the San Diego based DNA drug platform. The company is said to have designed the vaccine within three hours of acquiring the genetic sequence of the virus, and Zhejiang Tianyuan Biopharmaceutical Co. , a unit of step length pharmaceuticals, is developing a new coronavirus vaccine.

On February 11th the Imperial College London completed the world's first animal test of a new pneumonia vaccine, which has been given to mice; WHO Director General Tan Desai said in Geneva that the vaccine was expected to be ready within 18 months; Johnson & Johnson announced a partnership with Barda to develop a COVID-19 vaccine.

On 10 February, Moderna announced that mRNA-1273, a vaccine for COVID-19, had completed its first clinical manufacture on 7 February.

On Feb. 5, J & J will use its Ebola platform -- the platform for an adenovirus vector -- to develop a new vaccine. The vaccine will take at least eight months from development to production.

On February 3, GlaxoSmithKline (GSK) , a British pharmaceutical giant, announced it was joining the global effort to develop a new crown vaccine.

On January 31st the University of Saskatchewan in Canada began work on a new crown vaccine.

On January 29, researchers at the University of Queensland, Australia, plan to use the "molecular tweezers" patent technology to rapidly produce a new vaccine, the technology can increase the stability of the virus protein; Anhui Longkoma Biopharmaceutical Co. , Ltd. signed an agreement with the Institute of Microbiology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, based on the latter's relevant technical secrets and experience, lomacoma intends to transfer and follow-up industrialization of the development of new coronavirus recombinant protein subunit vaccine.

On 28 January, HKU's Department of Microbiology announced the development of a new crown vaccine based on the nasal flu vaccine, which can be tested in animals in the future to determine its efficacy and safety, the vaccine is expected to be ready for clinical trials in humans within a year, and the Shanghai Oriental Hospital Translational Medicine Platform is working with COVID-19 to promote the development of a vaccine for the gene. The technology is said to be able to produce and prepare large-scale vaccine samples within 40 days.

On January 26, Xu Wenbo, director of the virus institute at the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said the center had launched research and development of a new crown vaccine and had successfully isolated the virus and was screening seed strains.

Since the emergence of SARS, advances in coronavirus research and technology (MRNA technology) have dramatically shortened the time it takes to develop new coronaviruses, US health officials and researchers announced in the Jan. 23 issue of the Jama, the candidate vaccine for the new crown is expected to be ready for human clinical trials in three months.
